            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>What is a decibel (dB)?</h2>
              <p>
                A decibel (dB) is a logarithmic unit that expresses the ratio
                between two quantities, most often sound intensity or electrical
                power. For sound, it lets us compress an enormous range of
                intensities into manageable numbers and matches how our ears
                perceive loudness.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Core decibel formulas</p>
                <p>For power or intensity:</p>
                <p>\[ L = 10 \log_{10}\left(\frac{P}{P_0}\right) \]</p>
                <p>For sound pressure level (SPL):</p>
                <p>\[ L_p = 20 \log_{10}\left(\frac{p}{p_0}\right) \]</p>
                <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-gray-600">
                  In air, the reference pressure is usually \(p_0 =
                  20\,\mu\text{Pa}\), which corresponds roughly to the threshold
                  of human hearing at 1 kHz.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Why the decibel scale is logarithmic</h2>
              <p>
                Our ears can detect sounds from about 0 dB (threshold of
                hearing) up to 120–130 dB (pain). In terms of physical
                intensity, that is a range of about 10<sup>12</sup> (a trillion)
                to 1.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>+10 dB</strong> → 10× more intensity, perceived as
                  roughly twice as loud.
                </li>
                <li><strong>+20 dB</strong> → 100× more intensity.</li>
                <li><strong>+30 dB</strong> → 1,000× more intensity.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Using a logarithmic scale keeps the numbers small and makes it
                easier to compare levels and understand changes in loudness.
              </p>

              <h2>Typical sound levels in everyday life</h2>
              <table class="table-auto w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
                <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      Environment / source
                    </th>
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      Approx. level
                    </th>
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      Notes
                    </th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Threshold of hearing (1 kHz)
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">0 dB</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Young, healthy ears in very quiet conditions.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Rustling leaves, whisper
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">20–30 dB</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Very quiet environment.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Quiet office, normal conversation
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">50–60 dB</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Comfortable for most people.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Busy street, vacuum cleaner
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">70–80 dB</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Long-term exposure may contribute to hearing loss.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Lawn mower, loud traffic
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">85–90 dB</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Hearing protection recommended for extended periods.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Motorcycle, nightclub, live concert
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">95–110 dB</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Risk of damage in less than an hour without protection.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Sirens, rock concert near speakers
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">110–120 dB</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Very high risk; even short exposure can be harmful.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Jet engine at close range
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">130–140 dB</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Pain threshold; immediate danger to hearing.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>

              <h2>How to add decibel levels correctly</h2>
              <p>
                Decibels are logarithmic, so you cannot simply add them. To
                combine multiple independent sound sources:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Convert each level \(L_i\) from dB to linear intensity: \(I_i
                  \propto 10^{L_i/10}\).
                </li>
                <li>Sum the intensities: \(I_\text{total} = \sum I_i\).</li>
                <li>
                  Convert back to dB: \(L_\text{total} = 10
                  \log_{10}(I_\text{total})\).
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                Our “Add dB levels” tab does this automatically for any number
                of sources.
              </p>

              <h2>Distance and the inverse-square law</h2>
              <p>
                In open space, sound from a point-like source spreads out
                spherically. Intensity decreases with the square of the
                distance, so level changes with:
              </p>
              <p>\[ L_2 = L_1 - 20 \log_{10}\left(\frac{r_2}{r_1}\right) \]</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Double the distance → about <strong>−6 dB</strong>.</li>
                <li>Half the distance → about <strong>+6 dB</strong>.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Indoors, reflections, absorption and directionality of the
                source can change this behavior, but the formula is a useful
                first approximation.
              </p>

              <h2>Noise exposure and hearing safety</h2>
              <p>
                Many occupational standards use 85 dB for 8 hours as a reference
                limit, with a 3 dB “exchange rate”:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>85 dB → 8 hours</li>
                <li>88 dB → 4 hours</li>
                <li>91 dB → 2 hours</li>
                <li>94 dB → 1 hour</li>
                <li>97 dB → 30 minutes</li>
                <li>100 dB → 15 minutes</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Our exposure tab uses this rule to estimate a
                <em>rough</em> safe exposure time. Individual susceptibility
                varies, and some organizations use slightly different limits.
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                <strong>Important:</strong> This calculator is for educational
                and planning purposes only and does not replace professional
                hearing tests, occupational safety assessments, or medical
                advice.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">
                Decibel & noise pollution FAQ
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Is 85 dB really the “safe” limit?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    85 dB for 8 hours is a common occupational limit used by
                    agencies like NIOSH and many workplace regulations. It is
                    not a sharp boundary between “safe” and “unsafe”, but a
                    compromise between risk and practicality. Long-term exposure
                    below 70 dB is generally considered low risk for most
                    people, while regular exposure above 85 dB increases the
                    chance of permanent hearing loss over time.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How accurate are smartphone decibel meter apps?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Modern phones can give a rough indication of loudness,
                    especially if the app is calibrated, but they are not a
                    substitute for a properly calibrated sound level meter.
                    Microphone quality, directionality, wind noise and software
                    processing all affect accuracy. For regulatory or
                    occupational measurements, use professional instruments.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is the difference between dB(A), dB(C) and dB SPL?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    dB SPL is the raw sound pressure level. dB(A) and dB(C)
                    apply frequency weightings that approximate human hearing
                    sensitivity at different loudness levels. dB(A) is most
                    common for environmental and occupational noise limits.
                    dB(C) is sometimes used for peak levels or
                    low-frequency-rich sounds like explosions or bass-heavy
                    music.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can short bursts of very loud sound damage hearing?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Yes. Very loud impulsive sounds (e.g., gunshots, fireworks,
                    explosions) can cause immediate damage even if the total
                    exposure time is short. Peak levels above about 120–130 dB
                    are considered hazardous and warrant strong hearing
                    protection and distance from the source.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
            </section>
