l conversation at 1 m Long-term exposure is usually safe. The decibel (dB) scale is logarithmic. Every 10 dB increase means 10× more sound intensity and is perceived as roughly twice as loud. 30 dB – quiet library 60 dB – normal conversation 85 dB – busy traffic (hearing protection recommended for long exposure) 100 dB – nightclub, chainsaw 120 dB+ – rock concert, siren (pain threshold) Values are approximate and depend on distance, environment and measurement method. Sound pressure ↔ decibels Convert sound pressure to dB SPL (Sound Pressure Level) and back. Uses the standard reference pressure \(p_0 = 20 \,\mu\text{Pa}\) in air. Sound pressure Pa kPa MPa µPa Convert to dB SPL Formula: \(L_p = 20 \log_{10}(p / p_0)\), with \(p_0 = 20\,\mu\text{Pa}\). Sound level (dB SPL) Convert to pressure Formula: \(p = p_0 \cdot 10^{L_p/20}\). Power / intensity ↔ decibels Use this for acoustic intensity, electrical power, or any quantity where decibels are defined with a 10·log10 ratio. Power or intensity ratio (P / P₀) Convert to dB Formula: \(L = 10 \log_{10}(P/P_0)\). Level (dB) Convert to ratio Formula: \(P/P_0 = 10^{L/10}\). Add multiple sound levels (dB) Combine several independent sound sources correctly. You cannot just add dB values; this tool converts to linear intensity, sums, then converts back. Level 1, Level 2, Level at distance r₁ dB r₁ (m) r₂ (m) Calculate level at r₂ Formula: \(L_2 = L_1 - 20 \log_{10}(r_2 / r_1)\). Result: – In free field, doubling distance reduces level by about 6 dB. Indoors, reflections and absorption change this behavior. Approximate safe exposure time Estimate how long you can be exposed to a constant noise level before exceeding typical occupational limits. Uses an 85 dB for 8 hours baseline and a 3 dB exchange rate. Noise level (dB) Estimate safe exposure Each 3 dB increase halves the recommended exposure time. Estimated safe daily exposure: – Based on common occupational guidelines. Individual risk varies; this is not medical advice. What is a decibel (dB)? A decibel (dB) is a logarithmic unit that expresses the ratio between two quantities, most often sound intensity or electrical power. For sound, it lets us compress an enormous range of intensities into manageable numbers and matches how our ears perceive loudness. Core decibel formulas For power or intensity: \[ L = 10 \log_{10}\left(\frac{P}{P_0}\right) \] For sound pressure level (SPL): \[ L_p = 20 \log_{10}\left(\frac{p}{p_0}\right) \] In air, the reference pressure is usually \(p_0 = 20\,\mu\text{Pa}\), which corresponds roughly to the threshold of human hearing at 1 kHz. Why the decibel scale is logarithmic Our ears can detect sounds from about 0 dB (threshold of hearing) up to 120–130 dB (pain). In terms of physical intensity, that is a range of about 10 12 (a trillion) to 1. +10 dB → 10× more intensity, perceived as roughly twice as loud. +20 dB → 100× more intensity. +30 dB → 1,000× more intensity. Using a logarithmic scale keeps the numbers small and makes it easier to compare levels and understand changes in loudness. Typical sound levels in everyday life Environment / source Approx. level Notes Threshold of hearing (1 kHz) 0 dB Young, healthy ears in very quiet conditions. Rustling leaves, whisper 20–30 dB Very quiet environment. Quiet office, normal conversation 50–60 dB Comfortable for most people. Busy street, vacuum cleaner 70–80 dB Long-term exposure may contribute to hearing loss. Lawn mower, loud traffic 85–90 dB Hearing protection recommended for extended periods. Motorcycle, nightclub, live concert 95–110 dB Risk of damage in less than an hour without protection. Sirens, rock concert near speakers 110–120 dB Very high risk; even short exposure can be harmful. Jet engine at close range 130–140 dB Pain threshold; immediate danger to hearing. How to add decibel levels correctly Decibels are logarithmic, so you cannot simply add them. To combine multiple independent sound sources: Convert each level \(L_i\) from dB to linear intensity: \(I_i \propto 10^{L_i/10}\). Sum the intensities: \(I_\text{total} = \sum I_i\). Convert back to dB: \(L_\text{total} = 10 \log_{10}(I_\text{total})\). Our “Add dB levels” tab does this automatically for any number of sources. Distance and the inverse-square law In open space, sound from a point-like source spreads out spherically. Intensity decreases with the square of the distance, so level changes with: \[ L_2 = L_1 - 20 \log_{10}\left(\frac{r_2}{r_1}\right) \] Double the distance → about −6 dB . Half the distance → about +6 dB . Indoors, reflections, absorption and directionality of the source can change this behavior, but the formula is a useful first approximation. Noise exposure and hearing safety Many occupational standards use 85 dB for 8 hours as a reference limit, with a 3 dB “exchange rate”: 85 dB → 8 hours 88 dB → 4 hours 91 dB → 2 hours 94 dB → 1 hour 97 dB → 30 minutes 100 dB → 15 minutes Our exposure tab uses this rule to estimate a rough safe exposure time. Individual susceptibility varies, and some organizations use slightly different limits. Important: This calculator is for educational and planning purposes only and does not replace professional hearing tests, occupational safety assessments, or medical advice. Decibel & noise pollution FAQ Is 85 dB really the “safe” limit? 85 dB for 8 hours is a common occupational limit used by agencies like NIOSH and many workplace regulations. It is not a sharp boundary between “safe” and “unsafe”, but a compromise between risk and practicality. Long-term exposure below 70 dB is generally considered low risk for most people, while regular exposure above 85 dB increases the chance of permanent hearing loss over time. How accurate are smartphone decibel meter apps? Modern phones can give a rough indication of loudness, especially if the app is calibrated, but they are not a substitute for a properly calibrated sound level meter. Microphone quality, directionality, wind noise and software processing all affect accuracy. For regulatory or occupational measurements, use professional instruments. What is the difference between dB(A), dB(C) and dB SPL? dB SPL is the raw sound pressure level. dB(A) and dB(C) apply frequency weightings that approximate human hearing sensitivity at different loudness levels. dB(A) is most common for environmental and occupational noise limits. dB(C) is sometimes used for peak levels or low-frequency-rich sounds like explosions or bass-heavy music. Can short bursts of very loud sound damage hearing? Yes. Very loud impulsive sounds (e.g., gunshots, fireworks, explosions) can cause immediate damage even if the total exposure time is short. Peak levels above about 120–130 dB are considered hazardous and warrant strong hearing protection and distance from the source. About the author Ugo Candido builds financial tools and educational resources to help readers make better money decisions. He focuses on practical, transparent models that reflect how lenders calculate payments and total cost of ownership. Contact: info@calcdomain.com Editorial policy CalcDomain content is created for educational purposes and is reviewed for clarity, accuracy, and transparency. We do not accept paid placements that influence calculator outputs. Inputs and assumptions are shown directly in the interface so you can verify how results are produced. Methodology Results use standard formulas and the values you provide. Figures are estimates and may differ from lender quotes. For decisions that require professional guidance, consult a licensed advisor. Sources NIST: The International System of Units (SI) OpenStax: College Algebra Inputs used by this calculator Sound level (dB) 0 40 80 120 140+ 60 dB Normal conversation at 1 m Long-term exposure is usually safe. The decibel (dB) scale is logarithmic. Every 10 dB increase means 10× more sound intensity and is perceived as roughly twice as loud. 30 dB – quiet library 60 dB – normal conversation 85 dB – busy traffic (hearin